This flow is used for one of five operations related to NA Change Requests.  The inputs will be marked with what is required for each operation.

The five operations are (in order of precedence)\:

CANCEL- Cancel a scheduled change.
CONFIRM - Confirm a change as "Successful" or "Unsuccessful".
BACKOUT - Backout a change that's already run (within 24 hours).
RUNNOW - Run a script at the next earliest possible time.
SCHEDULE - Schedule the script to run at a specified time (default if no other operation is triggered)

Inputs\:
na_DeviceID - the HPNA Device ID for the NA Device
phost - Required for RUNNOW and SCHEDULE - Name of the device where the script will run (deprecated, fallback option)
phostType -  Required for RUNNOW and SCHEDULE - Type of device for phost (valid options are Firewall, Switch, or Router)
scriptName -  Required for RUNNOW and SCHEDULE - Name of the NA script
scriptVariables -  Required for RUNNOW and SCHEDULE - Variables for the NA script
startDateTime -  Required for ALL RUNS - The date and time to run the script (should be the current date/time for RUNNOW)
company -  Required for RUNNOW and SCHEDULE - Company of submitting user from ViewPoint
requested_by -  Required for RUNNOW and SCHEDULE - Email of submitting user from ViewPoint
sys_id - Required for CANCEL, CONFIRM, and BACKOUT - The ticket's sys_id
cancelScheduledChange -  Set to 'True' to perform a CANCEL operation -  Cancels a change that has already been scheduled.
confirmChange - Set to 'True' to perform a CONFIRM operation - Confirms a change that has already run as either successful or unsuccessful.
confirmationStatus - Required for CONFIRM - The status to the change to (valid options are Successful or Unsuccessful).
backoutChange -  Set to 'True' to perform a BACKOUT operation - Backs a change out according to the Backout Plan.  Also closes the ticket, opens a new 'backout' ticket, and cancels the scheduled ticket close flow.
runNow -  Set to 'True' to perform a RUNNOW operation - Runs a script at the earliest possible time and creates a ticket for the change.

Outputs\:
sys_id - The Service Now system identifier for the change.
ticketNum - The Change Ticket number in Service Now (eg CHG\#\#\#\#)
docRequestNum - The Request Ticket number for the Document Request (eg RITM\#\#\#\#)

Responses\:
Success - The requested operation completed successfully
Failure - There was an error attempting to complete the operation
cf83b307-a840-45c2-a522-cbfb1f2cc267.e14a5007-aea9-40f9-833b-8853fdb5e9d1.description=
Launches a specified flow immediately. See the notes below for more details.

Inputs\:
    centralServer - The host running the Central service.
Default value\: localhost.
    centralUsername - The username to use when connecting to the Central service.
    centralPassword - The password to use when connecting to the Central service.
    centralProtocol - The protocol used to communicate to the Central service.
Default value\: http.
Valid values\: http, https. 
    centralPort - The port the Central service is running on.
Default\: 8080.
    centralFlowPath - The UUID of the flow to launch.
    centralFlowLaunchWaitForFlow - A boolean value indicating whether the flow should run asynchronously, returning immediately. Otherwise, the operation waits for execution to complete.
Default value\: false 
Valid values\: false, true. 
    runName - The run name of the flow to launch.
    inputs - The list of input names (separated by delimiter) to pass to the invoked flow.
    values - The list of input values (separated by delimiter) to pass to the invoked flow.
    delimiter - The delimiter separating the items in lists.
Default value\: , (comma).

Results\:
    result - This is the primary output. The raw xml response of the Central server.
    runId - The id of the run.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\: 
1. If the targeted flow has specific names and values to be run with, then provide these by using "inputs" and "values" for them. 
Example\: If the "Generated Random Number" flow (found in\: Base/Library/Utility Operations/Samples) is needed to be run in Central then for "inputs" input provide\: min,max and for "values" input provide the inferior and superior limit to be used for generated number (i.e.\: 1,300).
2. You may add these inputs\:
    authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server.
Valid values\: basic, form, springForm, digest, ntlm, kerberos, anonymous (no authentication).
Default value\: anonymous - authentication not used when executing the request.
    proxy - The proxy server used to access the Central host.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port.
    proxyUsername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the "proxyUsername" input value.
    trustAllRoots - Specifies whether to enable weak security over SSL. An SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted certification authority issued it.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: true
    keystore - The location of the KeyStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS client authentication is used. The default value will be provided if "trustAllRoots" is "false".
Default\: "OO_Home"/java/lib/security/cacerts
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the KeyStore file. If "trustAllRoots" is "false" and "keystore" is empty, "keystorePassword" default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit
    trustKeystore - The location of the TrustStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS server authentication is used. The default value will be provided if "trustAllRoots" is "false".
Default\: "OO_Home"/java/lib/security/cacerts
    trustPassword - The password associated with the TrustStore file.  If "trustAllRoots" is "false" and "trustKeystore" is empty, "trustPassword" default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit 
3. You can use KeyTool to import a SSL certificate in a KeyStore. For example, to import a certificate in the Java cacerts KeyStore, run\: keytool -import -file c\:/../"your_cert".cer -alias "your_alias" -keystore "OO_Home"/java/lib/security/cacerts -keystorepass changeit. If the KeyStore does not exist, the command tries to create a new one containing only your certificate.
4. You can use KeyTool to create a certificate chain through the following command\: 
   keytool -genkey -dname "cn\=Mark Jones, ou\=JavaSoft, o\=Sun, c\=US" 
       -alias business -keypass kpi135 -keystore C\:\working\mykeystore 
       -storepass ab987c -validity 180
This creates a certificate chain in a new KeyStore containing only one certificate. It is useful in SSL client authentication because the KeyManager ignores any certificates not included in a certificate chain.
5. If the value assigned to the "trustAllRoots" input is "false" and "trustKeystore" is empty, the operation tries to use the default trust store, using the password "changeit". 
6. If the authentication type is Kerberos, you might need to add an SPN (Service Principal Name) for the web server's computer account.  In order to do this, you can use ADUC (Active Directory Users and Computers) with enabled "Advanced Features". Go to the web server's computer account (example\: CN\="web_server_name",CN\=Computers,DC\=domain,DC\=com), open the Properties window and press the "Attribute Editor" tab. Check the values of the "servicePrincipalName" attribute and add your SPN if not present. For example, http\://"web_server_FQDN"\:port.
7. Apache Tomcat is currently the only supported application server when using form-based authentication.
